1. API signature
String.prototype.codePointAt(index) -> integer | undefined

2. Parameters and return semantics
- index: zero-based integer (converted to integer; undefined -> 0).
- Returns: non-negative integer code point value at index; returns undefined if index out of range [0 .. str.length-1].
- If the element at index is a UTF-16 leading surrogate, returns the full code point of the surrogate pair (combining lead+trail). If index points to a trailing surrogate, returns the trailing surrogate code unit value only.

3. Unicode/UTF-16 behavior
- JavaScript strings are sequences of UTF-16 code units (0..65535). Code points > 0xFFFF are represented as surrogate pairs (two code units). codePointAt handles surrogate pairs by returning the combined code point when called on the leading surrogate index.
- Unicode code point range: 0 .. 0x10FFFF.

4. Usage patterns and iteration guidance
- Avoid iterating by index with codePointAt because surrogate pairs cause double-visiting; prefer for...of iteration or spreading the string into code-point units and then use element.codePointAt(0).
- Example pattern: for (const cp of str) { cp.codePointAt(0) } — iterates by code points.

5. Edge cases and return values
- codePointAt(index) returns undefined for index < 0 or index >= str.length.
- When index is provided on trailing-surrogate position, return value is the code unit value of trailing surrogate, not combined code point.

